<h1>Psalm 10</h1>
<div class="h1a">The just man's confidence in God in the midst of persecutions.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 11</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa009.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is split and known as <strong>Psalms 9 and 10</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end. A psalm to <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> In the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> I put my trust: how then do you say to my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>: Get thee away from hence to the mountain, like a sparrow.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> For, lo, the wicked have bent their bow: they have prepared their arrows in the quiver, to shoot in the dark the upright of heart.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For they have destroyed the things which thou hast made: but what has the <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a> <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> done?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is in his <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">temple</a>, the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord's</a> throne is in <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a>. His eyes look on the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12327a.htm">-->poor<!--</a>--> <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a>: his eyelids examine the sons of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> trieth the <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a> and the wicked: but he that <a href="../cathen/09397a.htm">loveth</a> <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>, <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hateth</a> his own <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> He shall rain snares upon sinners: fire and brimstone, and storms of winds, shall be the portion of their cup.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> For the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a>, and hath <a href="../cathen/09397a.htm">loved</a> <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a>: his countenance hath beheld righteousness.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa010001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa010002vul">2</span>&nbsp;In Domino confido; quomodo dicitis anim&aelig; me&aelig;:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Transmigra in montem sicut passer?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa010003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Quoniam ecce peccatores intenderunt arcum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> paraverunt sagittas suas in pharetra,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut sagittent in obscuro rectos corde:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa010004vul">4</span>&nbsp;quoniam qu&aelig; perfecisti destruxerunt;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> justus autem, quid fecit?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa010005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Dominus in templo sancto suo;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dominus in c&aelig;lo sedes ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Oculi ejus in pauperem respiciunt;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> palpebr&aelig; ejus interrogant filios hominum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa010006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Dominus interrogat justum et impium;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui autem diligit iniquitatem, odit animam suam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa010007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Pluet super peccatores laqueos;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ignis et sulphur, et spiritus procellarum, pars calicis eorum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa010008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Quoniam justus Dominus, et justitias dilexit:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> &aelig;quitatem vidit vultus ejus.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
