<h1>Psalm 11</h1>
<div class="h1a">The prophet calls for God's help against the wicked.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 12</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa010.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 11</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end: for the octave, a psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Save me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, for there is now no saint: truths are decayed from among the children of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> They have spoken vain things, every one to his neighbour: with deceitful lips, and with a double heart have they spoken.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> May the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> destroy all deceitful lips, and the tongue that speaketh <a href="../cathen/12405a.htm">proud</a> things.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Who have said: We will magnify our tongue: our lips are our own: who is <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> over us?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> By reason of the misery of the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12327a.htm">-->needy<!--</a>-->, and the groans of the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12327a.htm">-->poor<!--</a>-->, now will I arise, saith the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>. I will set him in safety: I will deal confidently in his regard.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> The words of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> are pure words: as silver tried by the fire, purged from the earth, refined seven times.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, wilt preserve us: and keep us from this <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generation</a> for ever.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> The <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">wicked</a> walk round about: according to thy highness, thou hast multiplied the children of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa011001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem, pro octava. Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa011002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Salvum me fac, Domine, quoniam defecit sanctus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam diminut&aelig; sunt veritates a filiis hominum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Vana locuti sunt unusquisque ad proximum suum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> labia dolosa, in corde et corde locuti sunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Disperdat Dominus universa labia dolosa,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et linguam magniloquam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Qui dixerunt: Linguam nostram magnificabimus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> labia nostra a nobis sunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Quis noster dominus est?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Propter miseriam inopum, et gemitum pauperum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> nunc exsurgam, dicit Dominus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Ponam in salutari;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> fiducialiter agam in eo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Eloquia Domini, eloquia casta; argentum igne examinatum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> probatum terr&aelig;, purgatum septuplum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Tu, Domine, servabis nos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et custodies nos a generatione hac in &aelig;ternum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa011009vul">9</span>&nbsp;In circuitu impii ambulant:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> secundum altitudinem tuam multiplicasti filios hominum.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
