<h1>Psalm 12</h1>
<div class="h1a">A prayer in tribulation.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 13</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa011.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 12</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, a psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"> How long, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, wilt thou forget me unto the end? how long dost thou turn away thy face from me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> How long shall I take counsels in my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>, sorrow in my heart all the day?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> How long shall my enemy be exalted over Me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> Consider, and hear me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>. Enlighten my eyes, that I never sleep in death:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Lest at any time my enemy say: I have prevailed against him. They that trouble me, will rejoice when I am moved:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> But I have trusted in thy mercy. My heart shall rejoice in thy <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a>: I will sing to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, who giveth me <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a> things: yea, I will sing to the <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a> of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, the most high.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa012001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Usquequo, Domine, oblivisceris me in finem?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> usquequo avertis faciem tuam a me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa012002vul">2</span>&nbsp;quamdiu ponam consilia in anima mea;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dolorem in corde meo per diem?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa012003vul">3</span>&nbsp;usquequo exaltabitur inimicus meus super me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa012004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Respice, et exaudi me, Domine Deus meus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Illumina oculos meos, ne umquam obdormiam in morte;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa012005vul">5</span>&nbsp;nequando dicat inimicus meus: Pr&aelig;valui adversus eum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Qui tribulant me exsultabunt si motus fuero;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa012006vul">6</span>&nbsp;ego autem in misericordia tua speravi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Exsultabit cor meum in salutari tuo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Cantabo Domino qui bona tribuit mihi;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et psallam nomini Domini altissimi.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
