<h1>Psalm 14</h1>
<div class="h1a">What kind of men shall dwell in the heavenly Zion.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 15</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa013.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 14</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> A psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, who shall dwell in thy tabernacle? or who shall rest in thy <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> hill?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> He that walketh without blemish, and worketh <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> He that speaketh <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a> in his heart, who hath not used deceit in his tongue: Nor hath done <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evil</a> to his neighbour: nor taken up a reproach against his neighbours.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> In his sight the malignant is brought to nothing: but he <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glorifieth</a> them that fear the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>. He that <a href="../cathen/11176a.htm">sweareth</a> to his neighbour, and deceiveth not;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> He that hath not put out his money to <a href="../cathen/15235c.htm">usury</a>, nor taken <a href="../cathen/02778c.htm">bribes</a> against the innocent: He that doth these things, shall not be moved for ever.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa014001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Domine, quis habitabit in tabernaculo tuo?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> aut quis requiescet in monte sancto tuo?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa014002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Qui ingreditur sine macula,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et operatur justitiam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa014003vul">3</span>&nbsp;qui loquitur veritatem in corde suo:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui non egit dolum in lingua sua,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> nec fecit proximo suo malum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et opprobrium non accepit adversus proximos suos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa014004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Ad nihilum deductus est in conspectu ejus malignus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> timentes autem Dominum glorificat.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Qui jurat proximo suo, et non decipit;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa014005vul">5</span>&nbsp;qui pecuniam suam non dedit ad usuram,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et munera super innocentem non accepit:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui facit h&aelig;c non movebitur in &aelig;ternum.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
