<h1>Psalm 18</h1>
<div class="h1a">The works of God show forth his glory: his law is greatly to be esteemed and loved.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 19</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa017.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 18</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end. A psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> The <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heavens</a> show forth the <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, and the <a href="../cathen/06079b.htm">firmament</a> declareth the work of his hands.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Day to day uttereth speech, and night to night showeth knowledge.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> There are no speeches nor languages, where their voices are not heard.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Their sound hath gone forth into all the earth: and their words unto the ends of the world.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> He hath set his tabernacle in the sun: and he as a bridegroom coming out of his bridechamber, Hath rejoiced as a giant to run the way:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> His going out is from the end of <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a>, And his circuit even to the end thereof: and there is no one that can hide himself from his heat.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> The <a href="../cathen/14779c.htm">law</a> of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is unspotted, converting <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">souls</a>: the testimony of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is faithful, giving wisdom to little ones.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> The justices of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> are right, rejoicing hearts: the commandment of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is lightsome, enlightening the eyes.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> The fear of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a>, enduring for ever and ever: the judgments of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> are <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">true</a>, justified in themselves.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> More to be desired than gold and many <a href="../cathen/14304c.htm">precious stones</a>: and sweeter than honey and the honeycomb.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> For thy servant keepeth them, and in keeping them there is a great reward.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> Who can understand <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sins</a>? from my secret ones cleanse me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> And from those of others spare thy servant. If they shall have no dominion over me, then shall I be without spot: and I shall be cleansed from the greatest <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse15">15</span> And the words of my mouth shall be such as may please: and the meditation of my heart always in thy sight. O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, my helper and my Redeemer.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa018001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa018002vul">2</span>&nbsp;C&aelig;li enarrant gloriam Dei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et opera manuum ejus annuntiat firmamentum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Dies diei eructat verbum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et nox nocti indicat scientiam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Non sunt loquel&aelig;, neque sermones,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quorum non audiantur voces eorum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018005vul">5</span>&nbsp;In omnem terram exivit sonus eorum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in fines orbis terr&aelig; verba eorum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018006vul">6</span>&nbsp;In sole posuit tabernaculum suum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et ipse tamquam sponsus procedens de thalamo suo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Exsultavit ut gigas ad currendam viam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018007vul">7</span>&nbsp;a summo c&aelig;lo egressio ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Et occursus ejus usque ad summum ejus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> nec est qui se abscondat a calore ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Lex Domini immaculata, convertens animas;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> testimonium Domini fidele, sapientiam pr&aelig;stans parvulis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Justiti&aelig; Domini rect&aelig;, l&aelig;tificantes corda;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> pr&aelig;ceptum Domini lucidum, illuminans oculos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Timor Domini sanctus, permanens in s&aelig;culum s&aelig;culi;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> judicia Domini vera, justificata in semetipsa,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018011vul">11</span>&nbsp;desiderabilia super aurum et lapidem pretiosum multum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et dulciora super mel et favum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Etenim servus tuus custodit ea;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in custodiendis illis retributio multa.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018013vul">13</span>&nbsp;Delicta quis intelligit?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ab occultis meis munda me;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018014vul">14</span>&nbsp;et ab alienis parce servo tuo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Si mei non fuerint dominati, tunc immaculatus ero,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et emundabor a delicto maximo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa018015vul">15</span>&nbsp;Et erunt ut complaceant eloquia oris mei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et meditatio cordis mei in conspectu tuo semper.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Domine, adjutor meus, et redemptor meus.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
