<h1>Psalm 22</h1>
<div class="h1a">God's spiritual benefits to faithful souls.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 23</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa021.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 22</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> A psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> ruleth me: and I shall want nothing. <span class="stiki"><strong>Ruleth me...</strong> In <a href="../cathen/07176a.htm">Hebrew</a>, <em>Is my shepherd</em>, viz., to feed, guide, and govern me.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> He hath set me in a place of pasture. He hath brought me up, on the water of refreshment:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> He hath converted my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>. He hath led me on the paths of <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a>, for his own <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name's</a> sake.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For though I should walk in the midst of the shadow of death, I will fear no <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evils</a>, for thou art with me. Thy rod and thy staff, they have comforted me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Thou hast prepared a table before me against them that afflict me. Thou hast anointed my head with oil; and my chalice which inebriateth me, how goodly is it!</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> And thy mercy will follow me all the days of my life. And that I may dwell in the <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">house of the Lord</a> unto length of days.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa022001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Dominus regit me, et nihil mihi deerit:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa022002vul">2</span>&nbsp;in loco pascu&aelig;, ibi me collocavit.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Super aquam refectionis educavit me;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa022003vul">3</span>&nbsp;animam meam convertit.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Deduxit me super semitas justiti&aelig;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> propter nomen suum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa022004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Nam etsi ambulavero in medio umbr&aelig; mortis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> non timebo mala, quoniam tu mecum es.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Virga tua, et baculus tuus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ipsa me consolata sunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa022005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Parasti in conspectu meo mensam</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> adversus eos qui tribulant me;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> impinguasti in oleo caput meum:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et calix meus inebrians, quam pr&aelig;clarus est!</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa022006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Et misericordia tua subsequetur me</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> omnibus diebus vit&aelig; me&aelig;;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et ut inhabitem in domo Domini</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in longitudinem dierum.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
