<h1>Psalm 23</h1>
<div class="h1a">Who are they that shall ascend to heaven: Christ's triumphant ascension thither.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 24</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa022.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 23</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> On the first day of the week, a psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"> The earth is the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord's</a> and the fulness thereof: the world, and all they that dwell therein.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> For he hath founded it upon the seas; and hath prepared it upon the rivers.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Who shall ascend into the mountain of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>: or who shall stand in his <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> place?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> The innocent in hands, and clean of heart, who hath not taken his <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> in vain, nor sworn deceitfully to his neighbour.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> He shall receive a <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">blessing</a> from the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, and mercy from <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> his Saviour.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> This is the <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generation</a> of them that seek him, of them that seek the face of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of <a href="../cathen/08261a.htm">Jacob</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Lift up your gates, O ye princes, and be ye lifted up, O eternal gates: and the King of Glory shall enter in.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Who is this King of Glory? the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> who is strong and mighty: the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> mighty in battle.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Lift up your gates, O ye princes, and be ye lifted up, O eternal gates: and the King of Glory shall enter in.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> Who is this King of Glory? the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> of <a href="../cathen/13286a.htm">hosts</a>, he is the King of Glory.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa023001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Prima sabbati. Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Domini est terra, et plenitudo ejus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> orbis terrarum, et universi qui habitant in eo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Quia ipse super maria fundavit eum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et super flumina pr&aelig;paravit eum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Quis ascendet in montem Domini?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> aut quis stabit in loco sancto ejus?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Innocens manibus et mundo corde,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui non accepit in vano animam suam,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> nec juravit in dolo proximo suo:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023005vul">5</span>&nbsp;hic accipiet benedictionem a Domino,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et misericordiam a Deo salutari suo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023006vul">6</span>&nbsp;H&aelig;c est generatio qu&aelig;rentium eum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qu&aelig;rentium faciem Dei Jacob.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Attollite portas, principes, vestras,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et elevamini, port&aelig; &aelig;ternales,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et introibit rex glori&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Quis est iste rex glori&aelig;?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dominus fortis et potens,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dominus potens in pr&aelig;lio.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Attollite portas, principes, vestras,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et elevamini, port&aelig; &aelig;ternales,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et introibit rex glori&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa023010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Quis est iste rex glori&aelig;?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dominus virtutum ipse est rex glori&aelig;.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
