<h1>Psalm 25</h1>
<div class="h1a">David's prayer to God in his distress, to be delivered, that he may come to worship him in his tabernacle.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 26</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa024.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 25</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, a psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"> Judge me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, for I have walked in my innocence: and I have put my trust in the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, and shall not be weakened.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Prove me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, and try me; burn my reins and my heart.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> For thy mercy is before my eyes; and I am well pleased with thy <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> I have not sat with the council of vanity: neither will I go in with the doers of <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">unjust</a> things.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> I have <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hated</a> the assembly of the malignant; and with the wicked I will not sit.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> I will <a href="../cathen/15557b.htm">wash my hands</a> among the innocent; and will compass thy <a href="../cathen/01360a.htm">altar</a>, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> That I may hear the voice of thy praise: and tell of all thy wondrous works.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> I have <a href="../cathen/09397a.htm">loved</a>, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, the beauty of thy house; and the place where thy <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> dwelleth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Take not away my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, with the wicked: nor my life with bloody <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> In whose hands are <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquities</a>: their right hand is filled with gifts.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> But as for me, I have walked in my innocence: <a href="../cathen/12681a.htm">redeem</a> me, and have mercy on me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> My foot hath stood in the direct way: in the churches I will <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> thee, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

