<h1>Psalm 29</h1>
<div class="h1a">David praises God for his deliverance, and his merciful dealings with him.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 30</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa028.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 29</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> A psalm of a canticle, at the <a href="../cathen/04673a.htm">dedication</a> of <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David's</a> house.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> I will extol thee, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, for thou hast upheld me: and hast not made my enemies to rejoice over me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, I have cried to thee, and thou hast healed me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> Thou hast brought forth, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> from hell: thou hast saved me from them that go down into the pit.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Sing to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, O ye his saints: and give praise to the memory of his <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holiness</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> For <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a> is in his indignation; and life in his <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a> will. In the evening weeping shall have place, and in the morning gladness.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> And in my abundance I said: I shall never be moved.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, in thy favour, thou gavest strength to my beauty. Thou turnedst away thy face from me, and I became troubled.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> To thee, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, will I cry: and I will make supplication to my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> What profit is there in my blood, whilst I go down to corruption? Shall dust confess to thee, or declare thy <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a>?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> hath heard, and hath had mercy on me: the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> became my helper.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Thou hast turned for me my mourning into <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a>: thou hast cut my <a href="../cathen/07113b.htm">sackcloth</a>, and hast compassed me with gladness:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> To the end that my <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> may sing to thee, and I may not regret: O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, I will give praise to thee for ever.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa029001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Psalmus cantici, in dedicatione domus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa029002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Exaltabo te, Domine, quoniam suscepisti me,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> nec delectasti inimicos meos super me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Domine Deus meus, clamavi ad te, et sanasti me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Domine, eduxisti ab inferno animam meam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> salvasti me a descendentibus in lacum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Psallite Domino, sancti ejus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et confitemini memori&aelig; sanctitatis ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Quoniam ira in indignatione ejus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et vita in voluntate ejus:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ad vesperum demorabitur fletus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et ad matutinum l&aelig;titia.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Ego autem dixi in abundantia mea:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Non movebor in &aelig;ternum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Domine, in voluntate tua pr&aelig;stitisti decori meo virtutem;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> avertisti faciem tuam a me, et factus sum conturbatus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Ad te, Domine, clamabo,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et ad Deum meum deprecabor.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Qu&aelig; utilitas in sanguine meo,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dum descendo in corruptionem?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> numquid confitebitur tibi pulvis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> aut annuntiabit veritatem tuam?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Audivit Dominus, et misertus est mei;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dominus factus est adjutor meus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Convertisti planctum meum in gaudium mihi;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> conscidisti saccum meum, et circumdedisti me l&aelig;titia:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa029013vul">13</span>&nbsp;ut cantet tibi gloria mea, et non compungar.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Domine Deus meus, in &aelig;ternum confitebor tibi.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
