<h1>Psalm 31</h1>
<div class="h1a">The second penitential psalm.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 32</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa030.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 31</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> To <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> himself, understanding.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> are they whose <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquities</a> are forgiven, and whose <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sins</a> are covered.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> is the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> to whom the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> hath not imputed <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>, and in whose spirit there is no guile.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Because I was silent my bones grew old; whilst I cried out all the day long. <span class="stiki"><strong>Because I was silent, etc...</strong> That is, whilst I kept silence, by concealing, or refusing to confess my <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sins</a>, thy hand was heavy upon me, etc.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For day and night thy hand was heavy upon me: I am turned in my anguish, whilst the thorn is fastened. <span class="stiki"><strong>I am turned, etc...</strong> That is, I turn and roll about in my bed to seek for ease in my pain whilst the thorn of thy <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a> pierces my flesh, and sticks fast in me. Or, I am turned: that is, I am <a href="../cathen/04347a.htm">converted</a> to thee, my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, by being brought to a better understanding by thy chastisements. In the <a href="../cathen/07176a.htm">Hebrew</a> it is, my moisture is turned into the droughts of the summer.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> I have acknowledged my <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a> to thee, and my <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">injustice</a> I have not concealed. I said I will confess against my self my <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">injustice</a> to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>: and thou hast forgiven the wickedness of my <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> For this shall every one that is <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">pray</a> to thee in a seasonable time. And yet in a flood of many waters, they shall not come nigh unto him.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Thou art my refuge from the trouble which hath encompassed me: my <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a>, deliver me from them that surround me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> I will give thee understanding, and I will instruct thee in this way, in which thou shalt go: I will fix my eyes upon thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Do not become like the horse and the mule, who have no understanding. With bit and bridle bind fast their jaws, who come not near unto thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> Many are the scourges of the sinner, but mercy shall encompass him that hopeth in the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Be glad in the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, and rejoice, ye <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a>, and <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a>, all ye right of heart.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa031001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Ipsi David intellectus.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Beati quorum remiss&aelig; sunt iniquitates,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et quorum tecta sunt peccata.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Beatus vir cui non imputavit Dominus peccatum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> nec est in spiritu ejus dolus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Quoniam tacui, inveteraverunt ossa mea,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dum clamarem tota die.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Quoniam die ac nocte gravata est super me manus tua,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> conversus sum in &aelig;rumna mea, dum configitur spina.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Delictum meum cognitum tibi feci,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et injustitiam meam non abscondi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dixi: Confitebor adversum me injustitiam meam Domino;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et tu remisisti impietatem peccati mei.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Pro hac orabit ad te omnis sanctus</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in tempore opportuno.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Verumtamen in diluvio aquarum multarum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ad eum non approximabunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Tu es refugium meum a tribulatione qu&aelig; circumdedit me;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> exsultatio mea, erue me a circumdantibus me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Intellectum tibi dabo, et instruam te in via hac qua gradieris;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> firmabo super te oculos meos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Nolite fieri sicut equus et mulus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quibus non est intellectus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> In camo et freno maxillas eorum constringe,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui non approximant ad te.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Multa flagella peccatoris;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sperantem autem in Domino misericordia circumdabit.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa031011vul">11</span>&nbsp;L&aelig;tamini in Domino, et exsultate, justi;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et gloriamini, omnes recti corde.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
