<h1>Psalm 35</h1>
<div class="h1a">The malice of sinners, and the goodness of God.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 36</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa034.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 35</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, for the servant of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> himself.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> The <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">unjust</a> hath said within himself, that he would <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>: there is no fear of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> before his eyes.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> For in his sight he hath done deceitfully, that his <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> may be found unto <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hatred</a>. <span class="stiki"><strong>Unto hatred...</strong> That is, hateful to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> The words of his mouth are <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> and guile: he would not understand that he might do well.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> He hath devised <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> on his bed, he hath set himself on every way that is not <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a>: but <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evil</a> he hath not <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hated</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, thy mercy is in <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a>, and thy <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a> reacheth even to the clouds.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Thy <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a> is as the mountains of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, thy judgments are a <a href="../cathen/01075d.htm">great deep</a>. Men and beasts thou wilt preserve, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> O how hast thou multiplied thy mercy, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>! But the children of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a> shall put their trust under the covert of thy wings.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> They shall be inebriated with the plenty of thy house; and thou shalt make them drink of the torrent of thy pleasure.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> For with thee is the fountain of life; and in thy light we shall see light.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Extend thy mercy to them that know thee, and thy <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a> to them that are right in heart.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Let not the foot of <a href="../cathen/12405a.htm">pride</a> come to me, and let not the hand of the sinner move me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> There the workers of <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> are fallen, they are cast out, and could not stand.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

