<h1>Psalm 40</h1>
<div class="h1a">The happiness of him that shall believe in Christ; notwithstanding the humility and poverty in which he shall come: the malice of his enemies, especially of the traitor Judas.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 41</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa039.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 40</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, a psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> himself.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> is he that understandeth concerning the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12327a.htm">-->needy<!--</a>--> and the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12327a.htm">-->poor<!--</a>-->: the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> will deliver him in the <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evil</a> day.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> preserve him and give him life, and make him <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">blessed</a> upon the earth: and deliver him not up to the will of his enemies.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> help him on his bed of sorrow: thou hast turned all his couch in his sickness.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> I said: O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, be thou merciful to me: heal my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>, for I have <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sinned</a> against thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> My enemies have spoken <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evils</a> against me: when shall he die and his <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a> perish?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> And if he came in to see me, he spoke vain things: his heart gathered together <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> to itself. He went out and spoke to the same purpose.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> All my enemies whispered together against me: they devised <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evils</a> to me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> They determined against me an <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">unjust</a> word: shall he that sleepeth rise again no more?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> For even the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> of my peace, in whom I trusted, who ate my bread, hath greatly supplanted me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> But thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, have mercy on me, and raise my up again: and I will requite them.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> By this I know, that thou hast had a <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a> will for me: because my enemy shall not rejoice over me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> But thou hast upheld me by reason of my innocence: and hast established me in thy sight for ever.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> be the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Israel</a> from eternity to eternity. So be it. So be it.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa040001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Psalmus ipsi David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa040002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Beatus qui intelligit super egenum et pauperem:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in die mala liberabit eum Dominus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Dominus conservet eum, et vivificet eum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et beatum faciat eum in terra,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et non tradat eum in animam inimicorum ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Dominus opem ferat illi super lectum doloris ejus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> universum stratum ejus versasti in infirmitate ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Ego dixi: Domine, miserere mei;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sana animam meam, quia peccavi tibi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Inimici mei dixerunt mala mihi:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Quando morietur, et peribit nomen ejus?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Et si ingrediebatur ut videret, vana loquebatur;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> cor ejus congregavit iniquitatem sibi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Egrediebatur foras et loquebatur.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040008vul">8</span>&nbsp;In idipsum adversum me susurrabant omnes inimici mei;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> adversum me cogitabant mala mihi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Verbum iniquum constituerunt adversum me:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Numquid qui dormit non adjiciet ut resurgat?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Etenim homo pacis me&aelig; in quo speravi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui edebat panes meos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> magnificavit super me supplantationem.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Tu autem, Domine, miserere mei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et resuscita me; et retribuam eis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040012vul">12</span>&nbsp;In hoc cognovi quoniam voluisti me,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam non gaudebit inimicus meus super me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040013vul">13</span>&nbsp;Me autem propter innocentiam suscepisti;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et confirmasti me in conspectu tuo in &aelig;ternum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa040014vul">14</span>&nbsp;Benedictus Dominus Deus Isra&euml;l</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> a s&aelig;culo et usque in s&aelig;culum. Fiat, fiat.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
