<h1>Psalm 41</h1>
<div class="h1a">The fervent desire of the just after God: hope in afflictions.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 42</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa040.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 41</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, understanding for the sons of <a href="../cathen/04361a.htm">Core</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> As the hart panteth after the fountains of water; so my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> panteth after thee, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> My <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> hath thirsted after the strong <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">living God</a>; when shall I come and appear before the face of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> My tears have been my bread day and night, whilst it is said to me daily: Where is thy <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> These things I remembered, and poured out my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> in me: for I shall go over into the place of the wonderful tabernacle, even to the <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">house of God</a>: With the voice of <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a> and praise; the noise of one feasting.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Why art thou sad, O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>? and why dost thou trouble me? Hope in <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, for I will still give praise to him: the <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a> of my countenance,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> And my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>. My <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> is troubled within my self: therefore will I remember thee from the land of <a href="../cathen/08501a.htm">Jordan</a> and Hermoniim, from the little hill.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> <a href="../cathen/01075d.htm">Deep</a> calleth on <a href="../cathen/01075d.htm">deep</a>, at the noise of thy flood-gates. All thy heights and thy billows have passed over me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> In the daytime the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> hath commanded his mercy; and a canticle to him in the night. With me is <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a> to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of my life.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> I will say to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>: Thou art my support. Why hast thou forgotten me? and why go I mourning, whilst my enemy afflicteth me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Whilst my bones are broken, my enemies who trouble me have reproached me; Whilst they say to me day be day: Where is thy <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Why art thou cast down, O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>? and why dost thou disquiet me? Hope thou in <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, for I will still give praise to him: the <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a> of my countenance, and my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa041001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Intellectus filiis Core.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa041002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Quemadmodum desiderat cervus ad fontes aquarum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ita desiderat anima mea ad te, Deus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Sitivit anima mea ad Deum fortem, vivum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quando veniam, et apparebo ante faciem Dei?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Fuerunt mihi lacrim&aelig; me&aelig; panes die ac nocte,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dum dicitur mihi quotidie: Ubi est Deus tuus?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041005vul">5</span>&nbsp;H&aelig;c recordatus sum, et effudi in me animam meam,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam transibo in locum tabernaculi admirabilis, usque ad domum Dei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in voce exsultationis et confessionis, sonus epulantis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Quare tristis es, anima mea?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et quare conturbas me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Spera in Deo, quoniam adhuc confitebor illi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> salutare vultus mei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041007vul">7</span>&nbsp;et Deus meus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Ad meipsum anima mea conturbata est:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> propterea memor ero tui de terra Jordanis et Hermoniim a monte modico.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Abyssus abyssum invocat, in voce cataractarum tuarum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> omnia excelsa tua, et fluctus tui super me transierunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041009vul">9</span>&nbsp;In die mandavit Dominus misericordiam suam,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et nocte canticum ejus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> apud me oratio Deo vit&aelig; me&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Dicam Deo: Susceptor meus es;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quare oblitus es mei?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et quare contristatus incedo, dum affligit me inimicus?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Dum confringuntur ossa mea,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> exprobraverunt mihi qui tribulant me inimici mei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dum dicunt mihi per singulos dies: Ubi est Deus tuus?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa041012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Quare tristis es, anima mea?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et quare conturbas me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Spera in Deo, quoniam adhuc confitebor illi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> salutare vultus mei, et Deus meus.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
