<h1>Psalm 42</h1>
<div class="h1a">The prophet aspires after the temple and altar of God.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 43</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa041.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 42</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"> A psalm for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Judge me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, and distinguish my cause from the nation that is not <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a>: deliver me from the unjust and deceitful <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> For thou art <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> my strength: why hast thou cast me off? and why do I go sorrowful whilst the enemy afflicteth me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Send forth thy light and thy <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a>: they have conducted me, and brought me unto thy <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> hill, and into thy tabernacles.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> And I will go in to the <a href="../cathen/01360a.htm">altar</a> of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>: to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> who giveth <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a> to my youth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> To thee, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, I will give praise upon the harp: why art thou sad, O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>? and why dost thou disquiet me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<!--note missing psalm 42:6 in the vulgate-->
<!--note--><p class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Hope in <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, for I will still give praise to him: the <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a> of my countenance, and my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa042001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Judica me, Deus, et discerne causam meam de gente non sancta:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ab homine iniquo et doloso erue me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa042002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Quia tu es, Deus, fortitudo mea: quare me repulisti?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et quare tristis incedo, dum affligit me inimicus?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa042003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Emitte lucem tuam et veritatem tuam:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ipsa me deduxerunt, et adduxerunt</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in montem sanctum tuum, et in tabernacula tua.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa042004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Et introibo ad altare Dei,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ad Deum qui l&aelig;tificat juventutem meam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Confitebor tibi in cithara, Deus, Deus meus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa042005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Quare tristis es, anima mea?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et quare conturbas me?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Spera in Deo, quoniam adhuc confitebor illi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> salutare vultus mei, et Deus meus.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
