<h1>Psalm 51</h1>
<div class="h1a">David condemns the wickedness of Doeg, and foretells his destruction.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 52</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa050.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 51</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, understanding for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>,</span>
<span class="pro002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> When Doeg the <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edomite</a> came and told <a href="../cathen/13486d.htm">Saul</a>: <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> went to the house of <a href="../cathen/01102d.htm">Achimelech</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Why dost thou <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> in malice, thou that art mighty in <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> All the day long thy tongue hath devised <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">injustice</a>: as a sharp razor, thou hast wrought deceit.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Thou hast <a href="../cathen/09397a.htm">loved</a> malice more than goodness: and <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> rather than to speak righteousness.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Thou hast <a href="../cathen/09397a.htm">loved</a> all the words of ruin, O deceitful tongue.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Therefore will <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> destroy thee for ever: he will pluck thee out, and remove thee from thy dwelling place: and thy root out of the land of the living.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> The <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a> shall see and fear, and shall laugh at him, and say:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Behold the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> that made not <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> his helper: But trusted in the abundance of his riches: and prevailed in his vanity.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> But I, as a fruitful olive tree in the <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">house of God</a>, have hoped in the mercy of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> for ever, yea for ever and ever.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> I will praise thee for ever, because thou hast done it: and I will wait on thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>, for it is <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a> in the sight of thy saints.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa051001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Intellectus David,</span>
<span class="pro002"><span class="verse" id="psa051002vul">2</span>&nbsp;cum venit Do&euml;g Idum&aelig;us, et nuntiavit Sauli: Venit David in domum Achimelech.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa051003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Quid gloriaris in malitia,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui potens es in iniquitate?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Tota die injustitiam cogitavit lingua tua;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sicut novacula acuta fecisti dolum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Dilexisti malitiam super benignitatem;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> iniquitatem magis quam loqui &aelig;quitatem.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Dilexisti omnia verba pr&aelig;cipitationis;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> lingua dolosa.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Propterea Deus destruet te in finem;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> evellet te, et emigrabit te de tabernaculo tuo,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et radicem tuam de terra viventium.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Videbunt justi, et timebunt;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et super eum ridebunt, et dicent:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Ecce homo qui non posuit Deum adjutorem suum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sed speravit in multitudine divitiarum suarum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et pr&aelig;valuit in vanitate sua.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Ego autem, sicut oliva fructifera in domo Dei;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> speravi in misericordia Dei, in &aelig;ternum et in s&aelig;culum s&aelig;culi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa051011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Confitebor tibi in s&aelig;culum, quia fecisti;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et exspectabo nomen tuum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam bonum est in conspectu sanctorum tuorum.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
