<h1>Psalm 53</h1>
<div class="h1a">A prayer for help in destress.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 54</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa052.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 53</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, in verses, understanding for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.</span>
<span class="pro002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> When the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a> of Ziph had come and said to <a href="../cathen/13486d.htm">Saul</a>: Is not <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> hidden with us? [1 Samuel 23.19]</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Save me, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, by thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>, and judge me in thy strength.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, hear my prayer: give ear to the words of my mouth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> For strangers have risen up against me; and the mighty have sought after my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>: and they have not set <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> before their eyes.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> For behold <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> is my helper: and the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is the protector of my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Turn back the <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evils</a> upon my enemies; and cut them off in thy <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> I will freely <a href="../cathen/13309a.htm">sacrifice</a> to thee, and will give praise, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, to thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>: because it is <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> For thou hast delivered me out of all trouble: and my eye hath looked down upon my enemies.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa053001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem, in carminibus. Intellectus David,</span>
<span class="pro002"><span class="verse" id="psa053002vul">2</span>&nbsp;cum venissent Ziph&aelig;i, et dixissent ad Saul: Nonne David absconditus est apud nos?</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa053003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Deus, in nomine tuo salvum me fac,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in virtute tua judica me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa053004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Deus, exaudi orationem meam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> auribus percipe verba oris mei.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa053005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Quoniam alieni insurrexerunt adversum me,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et fortes qu&aelig;sierunt animam meam,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et non proposuerunt Deum ante conspectum suum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa053006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Ecce enim Deus adjuvat me,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et Dominus susceptor est anim&aelig; me&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa053007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Averte mala inimicis meis;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in veritate tua disperde illos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa053008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Voluntarie sacrificabo tibi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et confitebor nomini tuo, Domine, quoniam bonum est.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa053009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Quoniam ex omni tribulatione eripuisti me,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et super inimicos meos despexit oculus meus.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
<blockquote class="copyright">Transcribed as part of the <a href="http://vulsearch.sourceforge.net">Clementine Vulgate Project</a><br>Please notify the original transcriber (little.mouth@soon.com) of any errors in this Latin edition</blockquote>

