<h1>Psalm 57</h1>
<div class="h1a">David reproves the wicked, and foretells their punishment.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 58</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa056.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 57</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, destroy not, for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>, for an inscription of a title.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> If in very deed ye speak <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a>: judge right things, ye sons of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> For in your heart you work <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>: your hands forge <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">injustice</a> in the earth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> The <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">wicked</a> are alienated from the womb; they have gone astray from the womb: they have spoken false things.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Their madness is according to the likeness of a serpent: like the deaf asp that stoppeth her ears:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Which will not hear the voice of the charmers; nor of the wizard that charmeth wisely.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> shall break in pieces their teeth in their mouth: the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> shall break the grinders of the lions.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> They shall come to nothing, like water running down; he hath bent his bow till they be weakened.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Like wax that melteth they shall be taken away: fire hath fallen on them, and they shall not see the sun.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> Before your thorns could know the brier; he swalloweth them up, as alive, in his <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a>. <span class="stiki"><strong>Before your thorns, etc...</strong> That is, before your thorns grow up, so as to become strong briers, they shall be overtaken and consumed by divine <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a>, swallowing them up, as it were, alive in his <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> The <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a> shall rejoice when he shall see the revenge: he shall <a href="../cathen/15557b.htm">wash his hands</a> in the blood of the sinner. <span class="stiki"><strong>Shall wash his hands, etc...</strong> Shall applaud the <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a> of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, and take occasion from the consideration of the punishment of the wicked to <a href="../cathen/15557b.htm">wash and cleanse his hands</a> from <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> And <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> shall say: If indeed there be fruit to the <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a>: there is indeed a <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> that judgeth them on the earth.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa057001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem, ne disperdas. David in tituli inscriptionem.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa057002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Si vere utique justitiam loquimini,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> recta judicate, filii hominum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Etenim in corde iniquitates operamini;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in terra injustitias manus vestr&aelig; concinnant.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Alienati sunt peccatores a vulva;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> erraverunt ab utero:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> locuti sunt falsa.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Furor illis secundum similitudinem serpentis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sicut aspidis surd&aelig; et obturantis aures suas,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057006vul">6</span>&nbsp;qu&aelig; non exaudiet vocem incantantium,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et venefici incantantis sapienter.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Deus conteret dentes eorum in ore ipsorum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> molas leonum confringet Dominus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Ad nihilum devenient tamquam aqua decurrens;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> intendit arcum suum donec infirmentur.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Sicut cera qu&aelig; fluit auferentur;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> supercecidit ignis, et non viderunt solem.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Priusquam intelligerent spin&aelig; vestr&aelig; rhamnum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sicut viventes sic in ira absorbet eos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057011vul">11</span>&nbsp;L&aelig;tabitur justus cum viderit vindictam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> manus suas lavabit in sanguine peccatoris.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa057012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Et dicet homo: Si utique est fructus justo,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> utique est Deus judicans eos in terra.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
