<h1>Psalm 58</h1>
<div class="h1a">A prayer to be delivered from the wicked, with confidence in God's help and protection. It agrees to Christ and his enemies the Jews.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 59</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa057.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 58</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, destroy not, for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> for an inscription of a title, when <a href="../cathen/13486d.htm">Saul</a> sent and watched his house to kill him. [1 Samuel 19.]</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Deliver me from my enemies, O my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>; and defend me from them that rise up against me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Deliver me from them that work <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>, and save me from bloody <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For behold they have caught my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>: the mighty have rushed in upon me:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Neither is it my <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>, nor my <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>: without <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> have I run, and directed my steps.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Rise up thou to meet me, and behold: even thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of <a href="../cathen/13286a.htm">hosts</a>, the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Israel</a>. Attend to visit all the nations: have no mercy on all them that work <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> They shall return at evening, and shall suffer hunger like dogs: and shall go round about the city.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Behold they shall speak with their mouth, and a sword is in their lips: for who, say they, hath heard us?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> But thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, shalt laugh at them: thou shalt bring all the nations to nothing.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> I will keep my strength to thee: for thou art my protector:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> My <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, his mercy shall prevent me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> shall let me see over my enemies: slay them not, lest at any time my people forget. Scatter them by thy power; and bring them down, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, my protector:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> For the <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a> of their mouth, and the word of their lips: and let them be taken in their <a href="../cathen/12405a.htm">pride</a>. And for their <a href="../cathen/09569a.htm">cursing</a> and lying they shall be talked of,</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> When they are consumed: when they are consumed by thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a>, and they shall be no more. And they shall know that <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> will rule <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Jacob</a>, and all the ends of the earth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse15">15</span> They shall return at evening and shall suffer hunger like dogs: and shall go round about the city.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse16">16</span> They shall be scattered abroad to eat, and shall murmur if they be not filled.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse17">17</span> But I will sing thy strength: and will extol thy mercy in the morning. For thou art become my support, and my refuge, in the day of my trouble.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse18">18</span> Unto thee, O my helper, will I sing, for thou art <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> my defence: my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> my mercy.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

