<h1>Psalm 59</h1>
<div class="h1a">After many afflictions, the Church of Christ shall prevail.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 60</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa058.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 59</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, for them that shall be changed, for the inscription of a title, to <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> himself, for doctrine,</span>
<span class="pro002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> When he set fire to Mesopotamia of <a href="../cathen/14399a.htm">Syria</a> and Sobal: and Joab returned and slew of <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edom</a>, in the vale of the saltpits, twelve thousand <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, thou hast cast us off, and hast destroyed us; thou hast been <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">angry</a>, and hast had mercy on us.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> Thou hast moved the earth, and hast troubled it: heal thou the breaches thereof, for it has been moved.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Thou hast shown thy people hard things; thou hast made us drink the wine of sorrow.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Thou hast given a warning to them that fear thee: that they may flee from before the bow: That thy beloved may be delivered.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Save me with thy right hand, and hear me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> hath spoken in his <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> place: I will rejoice, and I will divide <a href="../cathen/13771b.htm">Sichem</a>; and will mete out the vale of tabernacles.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Galaad is mine, and <a href="../cathen/09583c.htm">Manasses</a> is mine: and Ephraim is the strength of my head. <a href="../cathen/08536a.htm">Juda</a> is my king:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> <a href="../cathen/10409b.htm">Moab</a> is the pot of my hope. Into <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edom</a> will I stretch out my shoe: to me the foreigners are made subject. <span class="stiki"><strong>The pot of my hope...</strong> Or my watering pot. That is, a vessel for meaner uses, by being reduced to serve me, even in the meanest employments. Ibid. <strong>Foreigners...</strong> So the <a href="../cathen/12021c.htm">Philistines</a> are called, who had no kindred with the <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Israelites</a>; whereas the <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edomites</a>, <a href="../cathen/10409b.htm">Moabites</a>, etc., were originally of the same <a href="../cathen/05782a.htm">family</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Who will bring me into the strong city? who will lead me into <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edom</a>?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Wilt not thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, who hast cast us off? and wilt not thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, go out with our armies?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> Give us help from trouble: for vain is the <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a> of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> Through <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> we shall do mightily: and he shall bring to nothing them that afflict us.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa059001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem, pro his qui immutabuntur, in tituli inscriptionem ipsi David, in doctrinam,</span>
<span class="pro002"><span class="verse" id="psa059002vul">2</span>&nbsp;cum succendit Mesopotamiam Syri&aelig; et Sobal, et convertit Joab, et percussit Idum&aelig;am in valle Salinarum duodecim millia.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa059003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Deus, repulisti nos, et destruxisti nos;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> iratus es, et misertus es nobis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Commovisti terram, et conturbasti eam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sana contritiones ejus, quia commota est.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Ostendisti populo tuo dura;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> potasti nos vino compunctionis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Dedisti metuentibus te significationem,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut fugiant a facie arcus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut liberentur dilecti tui.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Salvum fac dextera tua, et exaudi me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Deus locutus est in sancto suo:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> l&aelig;tabor, et partibor Sichimam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et convallem tabernaculorum metibor.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Meus est Galaad, et meus est Manasses;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et Ephraim fortitudo capitis mei.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Juda rex meus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Moab olla spei me&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> In Idum&aelig;am extendam calceamentum meum:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> mihi alienigen&aelig; subditi sunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Quis deducet me in civitatem munitam?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quis deducet me usque in Idum&aelig;am?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059012vul">12</span>&nbsp;nonne tu, Deus, qui repulisti nos?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et non egredieris, Deus, in virtutibus nostris?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059013vul">13</span>&nbsp;Da nobis auxilium de tribulatione,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quia vana salus hominis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa059014vul">14</span>&nbsp;In Deo faciemus virtutem;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et ipse ad nihilum deducet tribulantes nos.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
