<h1>Psalm 60</h1>
<div class="h1a">A prayer for the coming of the kingdom of Christ, which shall have no end.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 61</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa059.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 60</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, in hymns, for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Hear, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, my supplication: be attentive to my <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> To thee have I cried from the ends of the earth: when my heart was in anguish, thou hast exalted me on a rock. Thou hast conducted me;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For thou hast been my hope; a tower of strength against the face of the enemy.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> In thy <a href="../cathen/14424b.htm">tabernacle</a> I shall dwell for ever: I shall be protected under the covert of thy wings.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> For thou, my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, hast heard my <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a>: thou hast given an inheritance to them that fear thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Thou wilt add days to the days of the king: his years even to <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generation</a> and <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generation</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> He abideth for ever in the sight of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>: his mercy and <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">truth</a> who shall search?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> So will I sing a psalm to thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a> for ever and ever: that I may pay my <a href="../cathen/15511a.htm">vows</a> from day to day.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa060001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. In hymnis David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa060002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Exaudi, Deus, deprecationem meam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> intende orationi me&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060003vul">3</span>&nbsp;A finibus terr&aelig; ad te clamavi, dum anxiaretur cor meum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in petra exaltasti me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Deduxisti me,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060004vul">4</span>&nbsp;quia factus es spes mea:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> turris fortitudinis a facie inimici.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Inhabitabo in tabernaculo tuo in s&aelig;cula;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> protegar in velamento alarum tuarum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Quoniam tu, Deus meus, exaudisti orationem meam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dedisti h&aelig;reditatem timentibus nomen tuum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Dies super dies regis adjicies;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> annos ejus usque in diem generationis et generationis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Permanet in &aelig;ternum in conspectu Dei:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> misericordiam et veritatem ejus quis requiret?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa060009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Sic psalmum dicam nomini tuo in s&aelig;culum s&aelig;culi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut reddam vota mea de die in diem.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
