<div id="springfield">
<span class="navb">< <a href="../bible/psa060.htm">BACK</a> | <a href="../bible/psa062.htm">NEXT</a> ></span>
<h1>Psalm 61</h1>
<div class="h1a">The prophet encourages himself and all others to trust in God, and serve him.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 62</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa060.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 61</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, for Idithun, a psalm of <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Shall not my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> be subject to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>? for from him is my <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> For he is my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> and my saviour: he is my protector, I shall be moved no more.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> How long do you rush in upon a <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a>? you all kill, as if you were thrusting down a leaning wall, and a tottering fence.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> But they have thought to cast away my price; I ran in thirst: they <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">blessed</a> with their mouth, but <a href="../cathen/09569a.htm">cursed</a> with their heart.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> But be thou, O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>, subject to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>: for from him is my patience.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> For he is my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> and my saviour: he is my helper, I shall not be moved.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> In <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> is my <a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">salvation</a> and my <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a>: he is the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of my help, and my hope is in <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Trust in him, all ye congregation of people: pour out your hearts before him. <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> is our helper for ever.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> But vain are the sons of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>, the sons of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a> are <a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">liars</a> in the balances: that by vanity they may together deceive. <span class="stiki"><strong>Are liars in the balances, etc...</strong> They are so vain and light, that if they are put into the scales, they will be found to be of no weight; and to be mere <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">-->lies<!--</a>-->, deceit, and vanity. Or, They are <a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">liars</a> in their balances, by weighing things by false weights, and preferring the temporal before the <a href="../cathen/05551b.htm">eternal</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Trust not in <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a>, and cover not robberies: if riches abound, set not your heart upon them.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> hath spoken once, these two things have I heard, that power belongeth to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> And mercy to thee, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>; for thou wilt render to every <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> according to his works.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa061001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem, pro Idithun. Psalmus David.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa061002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Nonne Deo subjecta erit anima mea?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ab ipso enim salutare meum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Nam et ipse Deus meus et salutaris meus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> susceptor meus, non movebor amplius.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Quousque irruitis in hominem?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> interficitis universi vos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> tamquam parieti inclinato et maceri&aelig; depuls&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Verumtamen pretium meum cogitaverunt repellere;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> cucurri in siti:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ore suo benedicebant,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et corde suo maledicebant.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Verumtamen Deo subjecta esto, anima mea,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam ab ipso patientia mea:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061007vul">7</span>&nbsp;quia ipse Deus meus et salvator meus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> adjutor meus, non emigrabo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061008vul">8</span>&nbsp;In Deo salutare meum et gloria mea;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Deus auxilii mei, et spes mea in Deo est.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Sperate in eo, omnis congregatio populi;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> effundite coram illo corda vestra:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Deus adjutor noster in &aelig;ternum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Verumtamen vani filii hominum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> mendaces filii hominum in stateris,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut decipiant ipsi de vanitate in idipsum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Nolite sperare in iniquitate,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et rapinas nolite concupiscere;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> diviti&aelig; si affluant, nolite cor apponere.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Semel locutus est Deus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> duo h&aelig;c audivi:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quia potestas Dei est,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa061013vul">13</span>&nbsp;et tibi, Domine, misericordia:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quia tu reddes unicuique juxta opera sua.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
