<h1>Psalm 62</h1>
<div class="h1a">The prophet aspires after God.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 63</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa061.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 62</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> A psalm of <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> while he was in the <a href="../cathen/04749a.htm">desert</a> of <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edom</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, to thee do I watch at break of day. For thee my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> hath thirsted; for thee my flesh, O how many ways!</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> In a <a href="../cathen/04749a.htm">desert</a> land, and where there is no way, and no water: so in the sanctuary have I come before thee, to see thy power and thy <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For thy mercy is better than lives: thee my lips will praise.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Thus will I <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> thee all my life long: and in thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a> I will lift up my hands.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Let my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> be filled as with marrow and fatness: and my mouth shall praise thee with joyful lips.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> If I have remembered thee upon my bed, I will meditate on thee in the morning:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Because thou hast been my helper. And I will rejoice under the covert of thy wings:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> My <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> hath stuck close to thee: thy right hand hath received me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> But they have fought my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> in vain, they shall go into the lower parts of the earth:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> They shall be delivered into the hands of the sword, they shall be the portions of foxes.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> But the king shall rejoice in <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, all they shall be praised that <a href="../cathen/11176a.htm">swear</a> by him: because the mouth is stopped of them that speak <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">wicked</a> things.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa062001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Psalmus David, cum esset in deserto Idum&aelig;&aelig;.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa062002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Deus, Deus meus, ad te de luce vigilo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Sitivit in te anima mea; quam multipliciter tibi caro mea!</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062003vul">3</span>&nbsp;In terra deserta, et invia, et inaquosa,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sic in sancto apparui tibi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut viderem virtutem tuam et gloriam tuam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Quoniam melior est misericordia tua super vitas,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> labia mea laudabunt te.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Sic benedicam te in vita mea,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in nomine tuo levabo manus meas.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Sicut adipe et pinguedine repleatur anima mea,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et labiis exsultationis laudabit os meum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Si memor fui tui super stratum meum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in matutinis meditabor in te.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Quia fuisti adjutor meus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in velamento alarum tuarum exsultabo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Adh&aelig;sit anima mea post te;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> me suscepit dextera tua.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Ipsi vero in vanum qu&aelig;sierunt animam meam:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> introibunt in inferiora terr&aelig;;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062011vul">11</span>&nbsp;tradentur in manus gladii:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> partes vulpium erunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa062012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Rex vero l&aelig;tabitur in Deo;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> laudabuntur omnes qui jurant in eo:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quia obstructum est os loquentium iniqua.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
