<h1>Psalm 64</h1>
<div class="h1a">God is to be praised in his Church, to which all nations shall be called.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 65</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa063.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 64</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> To the end, a psalm of <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>. The canticle of <a href="../cathen/08334a.htm">Jeremiah</a> and Ezechiel to the people of the captivity, when they began to go out. <span class="stiki"><strong>Of the captivity...</strong> That is, the people of the captivity of <a href="../cathen/02179b.htm">Babylon</a>. This is not in the <a href="../cathen/07176a.htm">Hebrew</a>, but is found in the ancient translation of the <a href="../cathen/13722a.htm">Septuagint</a>.</span></span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> A hymn, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, becometh thee in Sion: and a <a href="../cathen/15511a.htm">vow</a> shall be paid to thee in <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">Jerusalem</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> O hear my <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a>: all flesh shall come to thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> The words of the wicked have prevailed over us: and thou wilt pardon our transgressions.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> is he whom thou hast chosen and taken to thee: he shall dwell in thy <a href="../cathen/04445a.htm">courts</a>. We shall be filled with the <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a> things of thy house; <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> is thy <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">temple</a>,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Wonderful in <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">justice</a>. Hear us, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> our saviour, who art the hope of all the ends of the earth, and in the sea afar off.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Thou who preparest the mountains by thy strength, being girded with power:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Who troublest the depth of the sea, the noise of its waves. The <a href="../cathen/06422a.htm">Gentiles</a> shall be troubled,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> And they that dwell in the uttermost borders shall be afraid at thy signs: thou shalt make the outgoings of the morning and of the evening to be joyful.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> Thou hast visited the earth, and hast plentifully watered it; thou hast many ways enriched it. The river of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> is filled with water, thou hast prepared their food: for so is its preparation.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Fill up plentifully the streams thereof, multiply its fruits; it shall spring up and rejoice in its <!--original show-->showers.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Thou shalt <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> the crown of the year of thy goodness: and thy fields shall be filled with plenty.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> The beautiful places of the <a href="../cathen/04749a.htm">wilderness</a> shall grow fat: and the hills shall be girded about with <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a>,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> The rams of the flock are clothed, and the vales shall abound with corn: they shall shout, yea they shall sing a hymn.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa064001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem. Psalmus David, canticum Jeremi&aelig; et Ezechielis populo transmigrationis, cum inciperent exire.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa064002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Te decet hymnus, Deus, in Sion,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et tibi reddetur votum in Jerusalem.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Exaudi orationem meam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ad te omnis caro veniet.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Verba iniquorum pr&aelig;valuerunt super nos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et impietatibus nostris tu propitiaberis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Beatus quem elegisti et assumpsisti:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> inhabitabit in atriis tuis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Replebimur in bonis domus tu&aelig;;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sanctum est templum tuum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064006vul">6</span>&nbsp;mirabile in &aelig;quitate.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Exaudi nos, Deus, salutaris noster,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> spes omnium finium terr&aelig;, et in mari longe.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Pr&aelig;parans montes in virtute tua,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> accinctus potentia;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064008vul">8</span>&nbsp;qui conturbas profundum maris,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> sonum fluctuum ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Turbabuntur gentes,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064009vul">9</span>&nbsp;et timebunt qui habitant terminos a signis tuis;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> exitus matutini et vespere delectabis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064010vul">10</span>&nbsp;Visitasti terram, et inebriasti eam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> multiplicasti locupletare eam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Flumen Dei repletum est aquis; parasti cibum illorum:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam ita est pr&aelig;paratio ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Rivos ejus inebria;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> multiplica genimina ejus:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in stillicidiis ejus l&aelig;tabitur germinans.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Benedices coron&aelig; anni benignitatis tu&aelig;,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et campi tui replebuntur ubertate.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064013vul">13</span>&nbsp;Pinguescent speciosa deserti,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et exsultatione colles accingentur.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa064014vul">14</span>&nbsp;Induti sunt arietes ovium,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et valles abundabunt frumento;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> clamabunt, etenim hymnum dicent.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
