<h1>Psalm 65</h1>
<div class="h1a">An invitation to praise God.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 66</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa064.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 65</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em>Unto the end, a canticle of a psalm of the resurrection.</em>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Shout with <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a> to <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, all the earth,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Sing ye a psalm to his <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>; give <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> to his praise.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Say unto <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, How terrible are thy works, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>! in the multitude of thy strength thy enemies shall lie to thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> Let all the earth <a href="../cathen/01151a.htm">adore</a> thee, and sing to thee: let it sing a psalm to thy <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Come and see the works of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>; who is terrible in his counsels over the sons of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Who turneth the sea into dry land, in the river they shall pass on foot: there shall we rejoice in him.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Who by his power ruleth for ever: his eyes behold the nations; let not them that provoke him be exalted in themselves.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> O <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> our <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, ye <a href="../cathen/06422a.htm">Gentiles</a>: and make the voice of his praise to be heard.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Who hath set my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> to live: and hath not suffered my feet to be moved:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> For thou, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, hast proved us: thou hast tried us by fire, as silver is tried.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Thou hast brought us into a net, thou hast laid afflictions on our back:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Thou hast set <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a> over our heads. We have passed through fire and water, and thou hast brought us out into a refreshment.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> I will go into thy house with burnt <a href="../cathen/11215d.htm">offerings</a>: I will pay thee my <a href="../cathen/15511a.htm">vows</a>,</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> Which my lips have uttered, And my mouth hath spoken, when I was in trouble.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse15">15</span> I will offer up to thee <a href="../cathen/07396b.htm">holocausts</a> full of marrow, with burnt <a href="../cathen/11215d.htm">offerings</a> of rams: I will offer to thee bullocks with goats.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse16">16</span> Come and hear, all ye that fear <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, and I will tell you what great things he hath done for my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse17">17</span> I cried to him with my mouth: and I extolled him with my tongue.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse18">18</span> If I have looked at <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquity</a> in my heart, the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> will not hear me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse19">19</span> Therefore hath <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> heard me, and hath attended to the voice of my supplication.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse20">20</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> be <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, who hath not turned away my <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a>, nor his mercy from me.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

