<h1>Psalm 75</h1>
<div class="h1a">God is known in his Church: and exerts his power in protecting it. It alludes to the slaughter of the Assyrians, in the days of King Hezekiah.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 76</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa074.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 75</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unto the end, in praises, a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12533a.htm">-->psalm<!--</a>--> for Asaph: a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03301a.htm">-->canticle<!--</a>--> to the <a href="../cathen/02007c.htm">Assyrians</a>.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> In <a href="../cathen/08544a.htm">Judea</a> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> is <a href="../cathen/08673a.htm">known</a>: his <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a> is great in <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Israel</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> And his place is in <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">peace</a>: and his abode in <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">-->Sion<!--</a>-->:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> There hath he broken the powers of bows, the shield, the sword, and the battle.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Thou enlightenest wonderfully from the everlasting hills.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> All the foolish of heart were troubled. They have slept their sleep; and all the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a> of <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/15571a.htm">-->riches<!--</a>--> have found nothing in their hands.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> At thy rebuke, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> of <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Jacob</a>, they have all slumbered that mounted on horseback.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Thou art terrible, and who shall resist thee? from that <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14726a.htm">-->time<!--</a>--> thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a>. <span class="stiki"><strong>From that time, etc...</strong> From the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14726a.htm">-->time<!--</a>--> that thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a> shall break out.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Thou hast <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03459a.htm">-->caused<!--</a>--> judgment to be heard from <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a>: the earth trembled and was still,</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> When <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> arose in <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->judgment<!--</a>-->, to <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/13407a.htm">-->save<!--</a>--> all the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/07543b.htm">-->meek<!--</a>--> of the earth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> For the thought of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> shall give praise to thee: and the remainders of the thought shall keep holiday to thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> <a href="../cathen/15511a.htm">Vow</a> ye, and pay to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord your God</a>: all you that are round about him bring presents. To him that is terrible,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> Even to him who taketh away the <!--nnn--><!--<a href="../cathen/14220b.htm">-->spirit<!--</a>--> of princes: to the terrible with the kings of the earth.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa075001vul">1</span>&nbsp;In finem, in laudibus. Psalmus Asaph, canticum ad Assyrios.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001"><span class="verse" id="psa075002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Notus in Jud&aelig;a Deus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in Isra&euml;l magnum nomen ejus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Et factus est in pace locus ejus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et habitatio ejus in Sion.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Ibi confregit potentias arcuum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> scutum, gladium, et bellum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Illuminans tu mirabiliter a montibus &aelig;ternis;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075006vul">6</span>&nbsp;turbati sunt omnes insipientes corde.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dormierunt somnum suum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et nihil invenerunt omnes viri divitiarum in manibus suis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Ab increpatione tua, Deus Jacob,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> dormitaverunt qui ascenderunt equos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Tu terribilis es; et quis resistet tibi?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ex tunc ira tua.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075009vul">9</span>&nbsp;De c&aelig;lo auditum fecisti judicium:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> terra tremuit et quievit</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="psa075010vul">10</span>&nbsp;cum exsurgeret in judicium Deus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ut salvos faceret omnes mansuetos terr&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Quoniam cogitatio hominis confitebitur tibi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et reliqui&aelig; cogitationis diem festum agent tibi.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075012vul">12</span>&nbsp;Vovete et reddite Domino Deo vestro,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> omnes qui in circuitu ejus affertis munera:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> terribili,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa075013vul">13</span>&nbsp;et ei qui aufert spiritum principum:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> terribili apud reges terr&aelig;.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
