<h1>Psalm 89</h1>
<div class="h1a">A prayer for the mercy of God: recounting the shortness and miseries of the days of man.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 90</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa088.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 89</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> A <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a> of <a href="../cathen/10596a.htm">Moses</a> the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, thou hast been our refuge from <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generation</a> to <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generation</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Before the mountains were made, or the earth and the world was formed; from <a href="../cathen/05551b.htm">eternity</a> and to <a href="../cathen/05551b.htm">eternity</a> thou art <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Turn not <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> away to be brought low: and thou hast said: Be <a href="../cathen/04347a.htm">converted</a>, O ye <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01148a.htm">-->sons<!--</a>--> of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>. <span class="stiki"><strong>Turn not man away, etc...</strong> Suffer him not quite to perish from thee, since thou art pleased to call upon him to be <a href="../cathen/04347a.htm">converted</a> to thee.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> For a thousand years in thy sight are as yesterday, which is past. And as a watch in the night,</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Things that are counted nothing, shall their years be.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> In the morning <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> shall grow up like grass; in the morning he shall flourish and pass away: in the evening he shall fall, grow dry, and wither.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> For in thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a> we have fainted away: and are troubled in thy indignation.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> Thou hast set our <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">iniquities</a> before thy eyes: our <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09238c.htm">-->life<!--</a>--> in the light of thy countenance.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> For all our days are spent; and in thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a> we have fainted away. Our years shall be considered as a spider: <span class="stiki"><strong>As a spider...</strong> As frail and weak as a spider's web; and miserable withal, whilst like a spider we spend our bowels in weaving webs to catch flies.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> The days of our years in them are threescore and ten years. But if in the strong they be fourscore years: and what is more of them is labour and sorrow. For mildness is come upon us: and we shall be corrected. <span class="stiki"><strong>Mildness is come upon us, etc...</strong> <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God's</a> mildness corrects us; inasmuch as he deals kindly with us, in shortening the days of this miserable <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09238c.htm">-->life<!--</a>-->; and so weaning our affections from all its transitory enjoyments, and teaching us <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">true</a> wisdom.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Who <a href="../cathen/08673a.htm">knoweth</a> the power of thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">anger</a>, and for thy <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/06021a.htm">-->fear<!--</a>--></span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Can <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11151a.htm">-->number<!--</a>--> thy <a href="../cathen/01489a.htm">wrath</a>? So make thy right hand <a href="../cathen/08673a.htm">known</a>: and <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a> learned in heart, in wisdom.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> Return, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, how long? and be entreated in favour of thy servants.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> We are filled in the morning with thy mercy: and we have rejoiced, and are delighted all our days.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse15">15</span> We have rejoiced for the days in which thou hast <a href="../cathen/07543b.htm">humbled</a> us: for the years in which we have seen <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evils</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse16">16</span> Look upon thy servants and upon their <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>-->: and direct their children.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse17">17</span> And let the brightness of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord our God</a> be upon us: and direct thou the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>--> of our hands over us; yea, the work of our hands do thou direct.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa089001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Oratio Moysi, hominis Dei.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Domine, refugium factus es nobis</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> a generatione in generationem.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Priusquam montes fierent,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> aut formaretur terra et orbis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> a s&aelig;culo et usque in s&aelig;culum tu es, Deus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Ne avertas hominem in humilitatem:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et dixisti: Convertimini, filii hominum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Quoniam mille anni ante oculos tuos</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> tamquam dies hesterna qu&aelig; pr&aelig;teriit:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et custodia in nocte</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="psa089005vul">5</span>&nbsp;qu&aelig; pro nihilo habentur,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> eorum anni erunt.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Mane sicut herba transeat;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> mane floreat, et transeat;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> vespere decidat, induret, et arescat.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Quia defecimus in ira tua,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in furore tuo turbati sumus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Posuisti iniquitates nostras in conspectu tuo;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> s&aelig;culum nostrum in illuminatione vultus tui.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Quoniam omnes dies nostri defecerunt,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in ira tua defecimus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Anni nostri sicut aranea meditabuntur;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089010vul">10</span>&nbsp;dies annorum nostrorum in ipsis septuaginta anni.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Si autem in potentatibus octoginta anni,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et amplius eorum labor et dolor;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quoniam supervenit mansuetudo, et corripiemur.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089011vul">11</span>&nbsp;Quis novit potestatem ir&aelig; tu&aelig;,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et pr&aelig; timore tuo iram tuam</span>
<span class="poe003"><span class="verse" id="psa089012vul">12</span>&nbsp;dinumerare?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Dexteram tuam sic notam fac,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et eruditos corde in sapientia.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089013vul">13</span>&nbsp;Convertere, Domine; usquequo?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et deprecabilis esto super servos tuos.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089014vul">14</span>&nbsp;Repleti sumus mane misericordia tua;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et exsultavimus, et delectati sumus omnibus diebus nostris.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089015vul">15</span>&nbsp;L&aelig;tati sumus pro diebus quibus nos humiliasti;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> annis quibus vidimus mala.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089016vul">16</span>&nbsp;Respice in servos tuos et in opera tua,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et dirige filios eorum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa089017vul">17</span>&nbsp;Et sit splendor Domini Dei nostri super nos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et opera manuum nostrarum dirige super nos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et opus manuum nostrarum dirige.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
