<h1>Psalm 92</h1>
<div class="h1a">The glory and stability of the kingdom; that is, of the Church of Christ.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 93</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa091.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 92</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em>Praise in the way of a canticle, for <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> himself, on the day before the <a href="../cathen/13287b.htm">sabbath</a>, when the earth was founded.</em>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> hath reigned, he is clothed with beauty: the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is clothed with strength, and hath girded himself. For he hath established the world which shall not be moved.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> My throne is prepared from of old: thou art from everlasting.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> The floods have lifted up, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>: the floods have lifted up their voice. The floods have lifted up their waves,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> With the noise of many waters. Wonderful are the surges of the sea: wonderful is the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> on high.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Thy testimonies are become exceedingly credible: <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holiness</a> becometh thy house, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, unto length of days.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa092001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Laus cantici ipsi David, in die ante sabbatum, quando fundata est terra.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Dominus regnavit, decorem indutus est:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> indutus est Dominus fortitudinem, et pr&aelig;cinxit se.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Etenim firmavit orbem terr&aelig;, qui non commovebitur.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa092002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Parata sedes tua ex tunc;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> a s&aelig;culo tu es.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa092003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Elevaverunt flumina, Domine,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> elevaverunt flumina vocem suam;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> elevaverunt flumina fluctus suos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa092004vul">4</span>&nbsp;a vocibus aquarum multarum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Mirabiles elationes maris;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> mirabilis in altis Dominus.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa092005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Testimonia tua credibilia facta sunt nimis;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> domum tuam decet sanctitudo, Domine,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in longitudinem dierum.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
