<h1>Psalm 103</h1>
<div class="h1a">God is to be praised for his mighty works, and wonderful providence.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 104</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa102.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 103</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> For <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a> himself.<!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Bless</a> the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>: O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>, thou art exceedingly great. Thou hast put on praise and beauty:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> And art clothed with light as with a garment. Who stretchest out the <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a> like a pavilion:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Who coverest the higher rooms thereof with water. Who makest the clouds thy chariot: who walkest upon the wings of the winds.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> Who makest thy <a href="../cathen/01476d.htm">angels</a> <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14220b.htm">-->spirits<!--</a>-->: and thy <a href="../cathen/10326a.htm">ministers</a> a burning fire.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Who hast founded the earth upon its own bases: it shall not be moved for ever and ever.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> The deep like a garment is its clothing: above the mountains shall the waters stand.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> At thy rebuke they shall flee: at the voice of thy thunder they shall <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/06021a.htm">-->fear<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> The mountains <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01767a.htm">-->ascend<!--</a>-->, and the plains descend into the place which thou hast founded for them.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Thou hast set a bound which they shall not pass over; neither shall they return to cover the earth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> Thou sendest forth springs in the vales: between the midst of the hills the waters shall pass.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> All the beasts of the field shall drink: the wild asses shall expect in their thirst.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> Over them the birds of the air shall dwell: from the midst of the rocks they shall give forth their voices.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> Thou waterest the hills from thy upper rooms: the earth shall be filled with the fruit of thy <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>-->:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> Bringing forth grass for cattle, and herb for the service of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">men</a>. That thou mayst bring bread out of the earth:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse15">15</span> And that <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01358a.htm">-->wine<!--</a>--> may cheer the heart of <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a>. That he may make the face cheerful with oil: and that bread may strengthen <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man's</a> heart.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse16">16</span> The trees of the field shall be filled, and the <a href="../cathen/03473a.htm">cedars</a> of <a href="../cathen/09104a.htm">Libanus</a> which he hath planted:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse17">17</span> There the sparrows shall make their nests. The <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->highest<!--</a>--> of them is the house of the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/02576b.htm">-->heron<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse18">18</span> The high hills are a refuge for the harts, the rock for the <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->irchins<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse19">19</span> He hath made the moon for seasons: the sun <a href="../cathen/08673a.htm">knoweth</a> his going down.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse20">20</span> Thou hast appointed darkness, and it is night: in it shall all the beasts of the woods go about:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse21">21</span> The young lions roaring after their prey, and seeking their meat from <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse22">22</span> The sun ariseth, and they are gathered together: and they shall <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">-->lie<!--</a>--> down in their dens.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse23">23</span> <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">-->Man<!--</a>--> shall go forth to his work, and to his labour until the evening.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse24">24</span> How great are thy <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>-->, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>? thou hast made all things in wisdom: the earth is filled with thy <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/15571a.htm">-->riches<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse25">25</span> So is this great sea, which stretcheth wide its arms: there are creeping things without <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11151a.htm">-->number<!--</a>-->: Creatures little and great.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse26">26</span> There the ships shall go. This sea <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->dragon<!--</a>--> which thou hast formed to play therein.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse27">27</span> All expect of thee that thou give them food in season.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse28">28</span> What thou givest to them they shall gather up: when thou openest thy hand, they shall all be filled with <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse29">29</span> But if thou turnest away thy face, they shall be troubled: thou shalt take away their breath, and they shall fail, and shall return to their dust.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse30">30</span> Thou shalt send forth thy <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14220b.htm">-->spirit<!--</a>-->, and they shall be <a href="../cathen/04470a.htm">created</a>: and thou shalt renew the face of the earth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse31">31</span> May the <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> endure for ever: the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> shall rejoice in his <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse32">32</span> He looketh upon the earth, and maketh it tremble: he troubleth the mountains, and they smoke.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse33">33</span> I will sing to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> as long as I live: I will sing praise to my <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> while I have my being.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse34">34</span> Let my speech be acceptable to him: but I will take delight in the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse35">35</span> Let sinners be consumed out of the earth, and the <a href="../cathen/08010c.htm">unjust</a>, so that they be no more: O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>, <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> thou the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

