<h1>Psalm 104</h1>
<div class="h1a">A thanksgiving to God for his benefits to his people Israel.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 105</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa103.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 104</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em><a href="../cathen/01319b.htm">Alleluia</a>.</em>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Give <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">glory</a> to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, and call upon his <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>: declare his <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->deeds<!--</a>--> among the <a href="../cathen/06422a.htm">Gentiles</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Sing to him, yea sing praises to him: relate all his wondrous <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> <a href="../cathen/06585a.htm">Glory</a> ye in his <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a>: let the heart of them rejoice that seek the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> Seek ye the lord, and be strengthened: seek his face evermore.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Remember his marvellous <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>--> which he hath done; his wonders, and the <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->judgments<!--</a>--> of his mouth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> O ye seed of <a href="../cathen/01051a.htm">Abraham</a> his servant; ye <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">sons of Jacob</a> his chosen.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> He is the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord our God</a>: his <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->judgments<!--</a>--> are in all the earth.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> He hath remembered his covenant for ever: the word which he <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/04153a.htm">-->commanded<!--</a>--> to a thousand <a href="../cathen/06412c.htm">generations</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> Which he made to <a href="../cathen/01051a.htm">Abraham</a>; and his <a href="../cathen/11176a.htm">oath</a> to <a href="../cathen/08175a.htm">Isaac</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse10">10</span> And he appointed the same to <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Jacob</a> for a <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->law<!--</a>-->, and to <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Israel</a> for an everlasting testament:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse11">11</span> Saying: To thee <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/15624a.htm">-->will<!--</a>--> I give the land of <a href="../cathen/03569b.htm">Chanaan</a>, the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09366b.htm">-->lot<!--</a>--> of your inheritance.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse12">12</span> When they were but a small <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11151a.htm">-->number<!--</a>-->: yea very few, and sojourners therein:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse13">13</span> And they passed from nation to nation, and from one <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08646a.htm">-->kingdom<!--</a>--> to another people.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse14">14</span> He suffered no <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> to hurt them: and he reproved kings for their sakes.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse15">15</span> Touch ye not my <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->anointed<!--</a>-->: and do no <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">evil</a> to my <a href="../cathen/12477a.htm">prophets</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse16">16</span> And he called a famine upon the land: and he broke in pieces all the support of bread.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse17">17</span> He sent a <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> before them: <a href="../cathen/08506a.htm">Joseph</a>, who was sold for a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14039a.htm">-->slave<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse18">18</span> They <a href="../cathen/07543b.htm">humbled</a> his feet in fetters: the iron pierced his <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse19">19</span> Until his word came. The <a href="../cathen/13001a.htm">word of the Lord</a> inflamed him.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse20">20</span> The king sent, and he released him: the ruler of the people, and he set him at liberty.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse21">21</span> He made him master of his house, and ruler of all his <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12462a.htm">-->possession<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse22">22</span> That he might instruct his princes as himself, and teach his ancients wisdom.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse23">23</span> And <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Israel</a> went into <a href="../cathen/05329b.htm">Egypt</a>: and <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">Jacob</a> was a sojourner in the land of <a href="../cathen/03566b.htm">Cham</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse24">24</span> And he increased his people exceedingly: and strengthened them over their enemies.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse25">25</span> He turned their heart to <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hate</a> his people: and to deal <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">-->deceitfully<!--</a>--> with his servants. <span class="stiki"><strong>He turned their heart, etc...</strong> Not that <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> (who is never the author of <a href="../cathen/14004b.htm">sin</a>) moved the <a href="../cathen/05329b.htm">Egyptians</a> to <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hate</a> and <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11703a.htm">-->persecute<!--</a>--> his people; but that the <a href="../cathen/05329b.htm">Egyptians</a> took occasion of <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hating</a> and <a href="../cathen/08326b.htm">envying</a> them, from the sight of the benefits which <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> bestowed upon them.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse26">26</span> He sent <a href="../cathen/10596a.htm">Moses</a> his servant: <a href="../cathen/01003a.htm">Aaron</a> the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> whom he had chosen.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse27">27</span> He gave them power to show them <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/10338a.htm">-->signs<!--</a>-->, and his wonders in the land of <a href="../cathen/03566b.htm">Cham</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse28">28</span> He sent darkness, and made it obscure: and grieved not his words. <span class="stiki"><strong>Grieved not his words...</strong> That is, he was not wanting to fulfil his words: or he did not grieve <a href="../cathen/10596a.htm">Moses</a> and <a href="../cathen/01003a.htm">Aaron</a>, the carriers of his words: or he did not grieve his words, that is, his <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01148a.htm">-->sons<!--</a>-->, the <a href="../cathen/08193a.htm">children of Israel</a>, who enjoyed light whilst the <a href="../cathen/05329b.htm">Egyptians</a> were oppressed with darkness.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse29">29</span> He turned their waters into blood, and destroyed their fish.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse30">30</span> Their land brought forth frogs, in the inner chambers of their kings.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse31">31</span> He spoke, and there came divers sorts of flies and sciniphs in all their coasts. <span class="stiki"><strong>Sciniphs...</strong> See the annotation, <a href="../bible/exo008.htm#verse16">Exodus 8:16</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse32">32</span> He gave them hail for rain, a burning fire in the land.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse33">33</span> And he destroyed their vineyards and their fig trees: and he broke in pieces the trees of their coasts.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse34">34</span> He spoke, and the locust came, and the bruchus, of which there was no <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11151a.htm">-->number<!--</a>-->. <span class="stiki"><strong>Bruchus...</strong> An insect of the locust kind.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse35">35</span> And they devoured all the grass in their land, and consumed all the fruit of their ground.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse36">36</span> And he <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/07441a.htm">-->slew<!--</a>--> all the <a href="../cathen/06081a.htm">firstborn</a> in their land: the <a href="../cathen/06082a.htm">firstfruits</a> of all their labour.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse37">37</span> And he brought them out with silver and gold: and there was not among their <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/15039a.htm">-->tribes<!--</a>--> one that was feeble.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse38">38</span> <a href="../cathen/05329b.htm">Egypt</a> was glad when they departed: for the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/06021a.htm">-->fear<!--</a>--> of them <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08748a.htm">-->lay<!--</a>--> upon them.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse39">39</span> He spread a cloud for their protection, and fire to give them light in the night.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse40">40</span> They asked, and the quail came: and he filled them with the bread of <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse41">41</span> He opened the rock, and waters flowed: rivers ran down in the dry land.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse42">42</span> Because he remembered his <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> word, which he had spoken to his servant <a href="../cathen/01051a.htm">Abraham</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse43">43</span> And he brought forth his people with <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a>, and his chosen with <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">gladness</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse44">44</span> And he gave them the lands of the <a href="../cathen/06422a.htm">Gentiles</a>: and they possessed the labours of the people:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse45">45</span> That they might observe his <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08573a.htm">-->justifications<!--</a>-->, and seek after his <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->law<!--</a>-->. <span class="stiki"><strong>His justifications...</strong> That is, his <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/04153a.htm">-->commandments<!--</a>-->; which here, and in many other places of the <a href="../cathen/13635b.htm">scripture</a>, are called <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08573a.htm">-->justifications<!--</a>-->, because the keeping of them makes <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a>. The <a href="../cathen/12495a.htm">Protestants</a> render it by the word <em>statutes</em>, in favour of their <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/05075b.htm">-->doctrine<!--</a>-->, which does not allow <a href="../cathen/06636b.htm">good</a> <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01115a.htm">-->works<!--</a>--> to <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08573a.htm">-->justify<!--</a>-->.</span></span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

