<h1>Psalm 114</h1>
<div class="h1a">The prayer of a just man in affliction, with a lively confidence in God.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in many popular Bible translations, the psalm below is combined with the <strong><a href="../bible/psa115.htm">next psalm</a></strong> to form <strong>Psalm 116</strong>.</span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em><a href="../cathen/01319b.htm">Alleluia</a>.</em>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> I have <a href="../cathen/09397a.htm">loved</a>, because the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> will hear the voice of my <a href="../cathen/12345b.htm">prayer</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> Because he hath inclined his ear unto me: and in my days I will call upon him.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> The sorrows of death have compassed me: and the perils of hell have found me. I met with trouble and sorrow:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> And I called upon the <a href="../cathen/10675a.htm">name</a> of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>. O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, deliver my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is merciful and <a href="../cathen/08571c.htm">just</a>, and our <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a> showeth mercy.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> The <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> is the keeper of little ones: I was <a href="../cathen/07543b.htm">humbled</a>, and he delivered me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Turn, O my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a>, into thy rest: for the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> hath been bountiful to thee.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> For he hath delivered my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> from death: my eyes from tears, my feet from falling.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> I will please the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> in the land of the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09238c.htm">-->living<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa114001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Alleluja.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Dilexi, quoniam exaudiet Dominus</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> vocem orationis me&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Quia inclinavit aurem suam mihi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et in diebus meis invocabo.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Circumdederunt me dolores mortis;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et pericula inferni invenerunt me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Tribulationem et dolorem inveni,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114004vul">4</span>&nbsp;et nomen Domini invocavi:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> o Domine, libera animam meam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Misericors Dominus et justus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et Deus noster miseretur.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Custodiens parvulos Dominus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> humiliatus sum, et liberavit me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Convertere, anima mea, in requiem tuam,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> quia Dominus benefecit tibi:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114008vul">8</span>&nbsp;quia eripuit animam meam de morte,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> oculos meos a lacrimis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> pedes meos a lapsu.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa114009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Placebo Domino in regione vivorum.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
