<h1>Psalm 119</h1>
<div class="h1a">A prayer in tribulation.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 120</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa118.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 119</strong>.</span></p></span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<div class="stiki"><strong>A gradual canticle...</strong> The following <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12533a.htm">-->psalms<!--</a>-->, in <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11151a.htm">-->number<!--</a>--> fifteen, are called <a href="../cathen/06718a.htm">gradual psalms</a>, or <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03301a.htm">-->canticles<!--</a>-->, from the word <em>gradus</em>, signifying steps, <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01767a.htm">-->ascensions<!--</a>-->, or degrees: either because they were appointed to be sung on the fifteen steps, by which the people <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01767a.htm">-->ascended<!--</a>--> to the <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">temple</a>: or, that in the singing of them the voice was to be <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->raised<!--</a>--> by <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03539b.htm">-->certain<!--</a>--> steps or <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01767a.htm">-->ascensions<!--</a>-->: or, that they were to be sung by the people returning from their <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03315a.htm">-->captivity<!--</a>--> and <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01767a.htm">-->ascending<!--</a>--> to <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">Jerusalem</a>, which was seated amongst mountains. The <a href="../cathen/06001a.htm">holy fathers</a>, in a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/10663b.htm">-->mystical<!--</a>--> sense, understand these steps, or <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/01767a.htm">-->ascensions<!--</a>-->, of the degrees by which <a href="../cathen/03712a.htm">Christians</a> spiritually ascend to <a href="../cathen/15472a.htm">virtue</a> and <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11665b.htm">-->perfection<!--</a>-->; and to the <a href="../cathen/15073a.htm">true</a> <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">temple of God</a> in the <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heavenly</a> <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">Jerusalem</a>.</div>

<p>A <a href="../cathen/06718a.htm">gradual canticle</a>.</p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> In my trouble I cried to the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>: and he heard me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, deliver my <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> from <a href="../cathen/05649a.htm">wicked</a> lips, and a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">-->deceitful<!--</a>--> tongue.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> What shall be given to thee, or what shall be added to thee, to a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/09469a.htm">-->deceitful<!--</a>--> tongue?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> The sharp arrows of the mighty, with coals that lay waste.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> Woe is me, that my sojourning is prolonged! I have dwelt with the inhabitants of <a href="../cathen/03474a.htm">Cedar</a>:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> My <a href="../cathen/14153a.htm">soul</a> hath been long a sojourner.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> With them that <a href="../cathen/07149b.htm">hated</a> peace I was peaceable: when I spoke to them they fought against me without cause.
<!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa119001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Canticum graduum.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Ad Dominum cum tribularer clamavi,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et exaudivit me.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa119002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Domine, libera animam meam a labiis iniquis</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et a lingua dolosa.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa119003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Quid detur tibi, aut quid apponatur tibi</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ad linguam dolosam?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa119004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Sagitt&aelig; potentis acut&aelig;,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> cum carbonibus desolatoriis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa119005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Heu mihi, quia incolatus meus prolongatus est!</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> habitavi cum habitantibus Cedar;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa119006vul">6</span>&nbsp;multum incola fuit anima mea.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa119007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Cum his qui oderunt pacem eram pacificus;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> cum loquebar illis, impugnabant me gratis.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
