<h1>Psalm 126</h1>
<div class="h1a">Nothing can be done without God's grace and blessing.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 127</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa125.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 126</strong>.</span></p></span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em>A <a href="../cathen/06718a.htm">gradual canticle</a> of <a href="../cathen/14135b.htm">Solomon</a>.</em>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Unless the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> build the house, they labour in vain that build it. Unless the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> keep the city, he watcheth in vain that keepeth it.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> It is vain for you to <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12792a.htm">-->rise<!--</a>--> before light, <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12792a.htm">-->rise<!--</a>--> ye after you have sitten, you that eat the bread of sorrow. When he shall give sleep to his beloved, <span class="stiki"><strong>It is vain for you to rise before light...</strong> That is, your early <!--k03--><!--<a href="../cathen/xxyyyk.htm">-->rising<!--</a>-->, your labour and worldly solicitude, <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/15624a.htm">-->will<!--</a>--> be vain, that is, <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/15624a.htm">-->will<!--</a>--> avail you nothing, without the light, <a href="../cathen/06689a.htm">grace</a>, and <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">blessing</a> of <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">God</a>.</span></span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> Behold the inheritance of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> are children: the reward, the fruit of the womb.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> As arrows in the hand of the mighty, so the children of them that have been shaken.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> is the <a href="../cathen/09580c.htm">man</a> that hath filled the desire with them; he shall not be confounded when he shall speak to his enemies in the gate.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa126001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Canticum graduum Salomonis.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Nisi Dominus &aelig;dificaverit domum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in vanum laboraverunt qui &aelig;dificant eam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Nisi Dominus custodierit civitatem,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> frustra vigilat qui custodit eam.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa126002vul">2</span>&nbsp;Vanum est vobis ante lucem surgere:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> surgite postquam sederitis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui manducatis panem doloris.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Cum dederit dilectis suis somnum,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa126003vul">3</span>&nbsp;ecce h&aelig;reditas Domini, filii;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> merces, fructus ventris.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa126004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Sicut sagitt&aelig; in manu potentis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> ita filii excussorum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa126005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Beatus vir qui implevit desiderium suum ex ipsis:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> non confundetur cum loquetur inimicis suis in porta.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
