<h1>Psalm 133</h1>
<div class="h1a">An exhortation to praise God continually.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 134</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa132.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 133</strong>.</span></p></span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em>A <a href="../cathen/06718a.htm">gradual canticle</a>.</em>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Behold now <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> ye the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, all ye servants of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>: Who stand in the <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">house of the Lord</a>, in the <a href="../cathen/04445a.htm">courts</a> of the <a href="../cathen/14499a.htm">house of our God</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> In the nights lift up your hands to the <a href="../cathen/07386a.htm">holy</a> places, and <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> ye the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> May the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> out of <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">-->Sion<!--</a>--> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">bless</a> thee, he that made <a href="../cathen/07170a.htm">heaven</a> and earth.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa133001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Canticum graduum.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Ecce nunc benedicite Dominum, omnes servi Domini:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui statis in domo Domini,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in atriis domus Dei nostri.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa133002vul">2</span>&nbsp;In noctibus extollite manus vestras in sancta,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et benedicite Dominum.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa133003vul">3</span>&nbsp;Benedicat te Dominus ex Sion,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui fecit c&aelig;lum et terram.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
<blockquote class="copyright">Transcribed as part of the <a href="http://vulsearch.sourceforge.net">Clementine Vulgate Project</a><br>Please notify the original transcriber (little.mouth@soon.com) of any errors in this Latin edition</blockquote>

