<h1>Psalm 136</h1>
<div class="h1a">The lamentation of the people of God in their captivity in Babylon.</div>
<p><span class="stiki">Does this psalm differ from what you were expecting? Don't be confused. There are two systems for arranging the psalms: the <strong>Septuagint</strong> and the <strong>Masoretic</strong>. We use the Septuagint system here. In the Masoretic system, which is used in most modern Bible translations, this psalm is called <strong>Psalm 137</strong>, and the <strong><a href="../bible/psa135.htm">previous psalm</a></strong> is known as <strong>Psalm 136</strong>.</span></p></span></p>

<h2>English (Douay-Rheims)</h2>

<p><em>A <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/12533a.htm">-->psalm<!--</a>--> of <a href="../cathen/04642b.htm">David</a>, for <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08334a.htm">-->Jeremias<!--</a>-->.</em> <span class="stiki"><strong>For Jeremias...</strong> For the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14726a.htm">-->time<!--</a>--> of <a href="../cathen/08334a.htm">Jeremiah</a>, and the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03315a.htm">-->captivity<!--</a>--> of <a href="../cathen/02179b.htm">Babylon</a>.</span>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="verse1">1</span> Upon the rivers of <a href="../cathen/02179b.htm">Babylon</a>, there we sat and wept: when we remembered <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">-->Sion<!--</a>-->:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse2">2</span> On the willows in the midst thereof we hung up our instruments.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse3">3</span> For there they that led us into <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/03315a.htm">-->captivity<!--</a>--> required of us the words of songs. And they that carried us away, said: Sing ye to us a <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/07595a.htm">-->hymn<!--</a>--> of the songs of <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">-->Sion<!--</a>-->.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse4">4</span> How shall we sing the song of the <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a> in a strange land?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse5">5</span> If I forget thee, O <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">Jerusalem</a>, let my right hand be forgotten.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse6">6</span> Let my <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14776c.htm">-->tongue<!--</a>--> cleave to my jaws, if I do not remember thee: If I make not <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">Jerusalem</a> the beginning of my <a href="../cathen/07131b.htm">joy</a>.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse7">7</span> Remember, O <a href="../cathen/06608a.htm">Lord</a>, the children of <a href="../cathen/07638a.htm">Edom</a>, in the day of <a href="../cathen/08344a.htm">Jerusalem</a>: Who say: Rase it, rase it, even to the foundation thereof.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse8">8</span> O daughter of <a href="../cathen/02179b.htm">Babylon</a>, miserable: <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">blessed</a> shall he be who shall repay thee thy payment which thou hast paid us.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="verse9">9</span> <a href="../cathen/02599b.htm">Blessed</a> be he that shall take and dash thy little ones against the rock. <span class="stiki"><strong>Dash thy little ones, etc...</strong> In the <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/14220b.htm">-->spiritual<!--</a>--> sense, we dash the little ones of <a href="../cathen/02179b.htm">Babylon</a> against the rock, when we mortify our <!--k07--><!--<a href="../cathen/11534a.htm">-->passions<!--</a>-->, and stifle the first motions of them, by a speedy recourse to the rock which is <a href="../cathen/08374c.htm">Christ</a>.</span>
<!--poepar--></blockquote>

<blockquote class="copyright">Old Testament first published 1609 by the English College at Douay<br />New Testament first published 1582 by the English College at Rheims<br />Revised and Annotated 1749 by Bishop Richard Challoner<br /><em>Imprimatur.</em> +James Cardinal Gibbons, Archbishop of Baltimore, September 1, 1899</blockquote>

<h2>Latin (Clementine Vulgate)</h2>
<!--propar--><p class="bibleprose"><span class="pro000"><span class="verse" id="psa136001vul">1</span>&nbsp;Psalmus David, Jeremi&aelig;.</span><!--/propar--></p>
<!--poepar--><blockquote class="biblepoem"><span class="poe001">Super flumina Babylonis illic sedimus et flevimus,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> cum recordaremur Sion.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136002vul">2</span>&nbsp;In salicibus in medio ejus</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> suspendimus organa nostra:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136003vul">3</span>&nbsp;quia illic interrogaverunt nos, qui captivos duxerunt nos,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> verba cantionum;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et qui abduxerunt nos:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> Hymnum cantate nobis de canticis Sion.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136004vul">4</span>&nbsp;Quomodo cantabimus canticum Domini</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in terra aliena?</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136005vul">5</span>&nbsp;Si oblitus fuero tui, Jerusalem,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> oblivioni detur dextera mea.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136006vul">6</span>&nbsp;Adh&aelig;reat lingua mea faucibus meis,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> si non meminero tui;</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> si non proposuero Jerusalem</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in principio l&aelig;titi&aelig; me&aelig;.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136007vul">7</span>&nbsp;Memor esto, Domine, filiorum Edom,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> in die Jerusalem:</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> qui dicunt: Exinanite, exinanite</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> usque ad fundamentum in ea.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136008vul">8</span>&nbsp;Filia Babylonis misera! beatus qui retribuet tibi</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> retributionem tuam quam retribuisti nobis.</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"><span class="verse" id="psa136009vul">9</span>&nbsp;Beatus qui tenebit,</span><!--poebre--><br />
<span class="poe002"> et allidet parvulos tuos ad petram.</span><!--poepar--></blockquote>
